1. Vision & Positioning
One-liner: A Gen-Z streetwear brand that turns corporate suffering into wearable protest — quirky, brutally honest T-shirts about work-from-home wars, toxic managers, appraisal season, notice periods, and every other soul-crushing cubicle ritual.

The insight: Gen Z is flooding into corporate jobs and hating the theatre of it — the standups, the "circle back", the "let's take this offline", the appraisal that gives you 8%. They cope with humor. Wearing a shirt that mocks the manager is a low-risk act of rebellion and an in-group signal. This is the "corporate life" niche — NOT an AI niche.

Positioning statement: For the fresher-to-mid-career professional who thinks corporate culture is a joke, [BRAND] makes the T-shirt that says it out loud — so you don't have to.

Why it can work commercially: "Corporate humor" / "office humor" apparel is a proven, active trend (relatable-slogan tees consistently sell on Instagram, Amazon, Etsy, and D2C stores). The differentiator here is (a) a tiered "how brave are you" system, (b) a genuinely wild storytelling website, and (c) an AI engine that lets the brand ship new, on-trend slogans faster than any competitor.

[OWNER-INPUT] Confirm target buyer age band (recommended 20–30) and whether we also target college students (final-year, about to enter corporate) as a secondary segment — the website's "university → corporate" narrative deliberately courts both.


