5. The Signature "University → Corporate" Scroll Experience
This is the wow page — the homepage as a scroll-driven narrative that takes the visitor from carefree university life down into corporate reality, with products woven into the story. This is the brand's moat and the "crazy graphics" the owner wants.
5.1 Narrative arc (top → bottom)
Act 0 — The Hook (hero): Full-viewport. Big wordmark, tagline, one CTA ("Shop the protest"). A subtle animated background (see §14). Scroll cue.
Act 1 — University: Bright, chaotic, hopeful. Confetti/graduation, "You did it!" energy. Copy: "They said the real world would be great." Featured: Tier 1 "Fresher Life" tees.
Act 2 — The Descent (onboarding): Colors drain toward corporate navy/grey as you scroll. ID card lanyard drops in. "Day 1", the org chart, the standup. Featured: Meetings collection.
Act 3 — Corporate Reality: Grey cubicles, the manager, appraisal, EMI, Monday. Peak irony. Featured: Tier 2 + Tier 3 hero products. The Operator collection gets a spotlight.
Act 4 — The Rebellion (turn): Highlighter yellow floods back in. "So we made the shirt." Product grid CTA, tier selector ("How brave are you?").
Act 5 — Footer / CTA: Newsletter ("Join the cult"), Instagram feed, team-pack upsell.
5.2 Interaction design
Scroll-driven, but performance-budgeted. Use GSAP + ScrollTrigger (or Framer Motion scroll) with IntersectionObserver fallbacks. Pin sections, tie color transitions and parallax to scroll progress.
Optional 3D moment: one Three.js / React-Three-Fiber scene — a slowly rotating T-shirt or a cubicle that assembles as you scroll. Lazy-loaded, only on capable devices (prefers-reduced- motion and device-tier checks disable it).
Reduced motion: if prefers-reduced-motion: reduce, replace scroll animation with clean static sections. This is mandatory, not optional.
Mobile: the narrative collapses into snappy, swipe-friendly panels — no janky heavy 3D on low-end phones. Ship a lightweight variant.
Performance budget: homepage LCP < 2.5s on 4G, total JS for the hero < ~200KB gzipped before hydration; heavy libs (Three.js/GSAP) code-split and loaded after first paint.
5.3 Accessibility
All narrative content must be readable and shoppable without JS animations.
Every product reachable via the normal /shop catalog too — the story is a layer, not a gate.


